{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17586004","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17586004"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:23:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:23:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15046"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15046","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15046"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.29,0.16,0.35,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7734"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67569"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7734","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7734"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15046"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53021"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5090"},{"type":"tags","id":"7875"},{"type":"tags","id":"8115"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18888"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18891"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67569","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67569"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA kidney biopsy specimen is obtained from a patient with multiple myeloma showing evidence of renal involvement.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following combinations is most likely to be visualised on histological examination?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Epithelial cast and granuloma","Tamm-Horsfall protein and light chain protein","Fatty cast and light chain protein","Light chain protein and multinucleated giant cell","Tamm-Horsfall protein and multinucleated giant cell"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn multiple myeloma with renal involvement, histological examination typically reveals \u003Cstrong\u003ETamm-Horsfall protein\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Elight chain protein\u003C/strong\u003E casts within the renal tubules. Tamm-Horsfall protein is a normal constituent of renal tubules and forms the matrix of urinary casts. Light chain proteins (Bence-Jones proteins) are immunoglobulin light chains produced by malignant plasma cells that precipitate in the tubules, leading to cast formation and eventual renal damage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpithelial casts\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Egranulomas\u003C/strong\u003E are seen in acute tubular injury and granulomatous conditions respectively, not in myeloma\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFatty casts\u003C/strong\u003E are associated with nephrotic syndrome\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMultinucleated giant cells\u003C/strong\u003E are characteristic of granulomatous conditions, not myeloma\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe combination of Tamm-Horsfall protein and light chain proteins forms the characteristic \u0027myeloma kidney\u0027 appearance with fractured, waxy casts in dilated tubules.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Multiple myeloma commonly shows light chain (Bence-Jones) protein casts in renal tubules on histology","Tamm-Horsfall protein is normally present in renal tubules and can form the matrix of urinary casts","Cast nephropathy in multiple myeloma occurs when excess light chains interact with Tamm-Horsfall protein"],"references":["Cowan AJ, Green DJ, Kwok M, Lee S, Coffey DG, Holmberg LA, Tuazon S, Gopal AK, Libby EN. Diagnosis and Management of Multiple Myeloma: A Review. JAMA. 2022 Feb 1;327(5):464-477. doi: 10.1001/jama.2022.0003. PMID: 35103762.","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53021"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15046"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53021","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53021"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-05T19:15:58+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-05T19:17:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7734"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67569"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCoun